5.2  SQL Implementation of the Data Warehouse
After designing the dimensional model, the data warehouse schema was implemented in SQL Server. A separate database named DWBI_Project was created to store the data warehouse tables.
The implementation included the creation of all dimension tables and the fact table according to the star schema design. The DimDate table was created first and populated with date values covering the required time period for the analysis. After that, the remaining dimension tables such as DimCustomer, DimProduct, DimEmployee, DimShipper, and DimCategory were created.
The FactSales table was then created with foreign key relationships connecting it to the dimension tables. The table also included business transaction fields such as OrderID and ProductID, together with the main measures Quantity, UnitPrice, Discount, and SalesAmount.
 
During the implementation, surrogate keys were used as primary keys for all dimension tables. These keys were generated using identity columns, while the original source keys were stored as business reference attributes.
Special consideration was given to the Slowly Changing Dimension design in DimCustomer, where the attributes StartDate, EndDate, and IsCurrent were included to support historical tracking of customer changes.
This SQL implementation provided the physical structure required for loading data through SSIS and ensured that the warehouse schema was ready for analytical querying.
 
5.3 Assumptions Made in the Design
Several assumptions were made during the design of the data warehouse. The FactSales table was designed at the grain of one product line item in one order. This means each record in the fact table represents one product sold within a specific order.
The DimCustomer table was selected as the Slowly Changing Dimension because customer details such as city, country, or contact information can change over time.
The DimDate table was generated separately to support time-based analysis and to avoid date lookup failures during ETL processing.
The product category was treated as a separate dimension to support category-level analysis. In addition, surrogate keys were used for all dimensions to maintain consistency and improve query performance in the warehouse.


6 .     ETL development
The ETL process for this project was developed using SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS). The main purpose of the ETL process was to extract data from multiple source systems, transform it into the required format, and load it into the data warehouse.
To manage the ETL flow properly, the implementation was divided into two main stages. In the first stage, data from the source systems was loaded into a staging database. In the second stage, the data was transformed and loaded from the staging database into the dimensional data warehouse.
The ETL process used three different source types: CSV files, an Excel file, and a SQL Server database. This helped to demonstrate the integration of data from multiple formats into a unified warehouse system.

6.1 Loading Data into the Staging Area
The first ETL package, Load_Staging.dtsx, was developed to load data from the different source systems into the staging database named DWBI_Staging.
The following staging tables were created and loaded:
• StgEmployee 
• StgOrder 
• StgOrderDetails 
• StgCustomer 
• StgCategory 
• StgShipper 
• StgProduct 
Employees, Orders, and Order Details were extracted from the SQL Server source database (DWBI_Source_DB). Customers, Categories, and Shippers were extracted from CSV files. Product data was extracted from the Excel file.
Before loading data into each staging table, truncation logic was applied using the OnPreExecute event handler in SSIS. This was done to avoid duplicate records when the package was executed multiple times.







