6.2 Loading Data into the Data Warehouse
The second ETL package, Load_DW.dtsx, was used to transform and load data from the staging database into the data warehouse (DWBI_Project).
The dimension tables were loaded first in the following order:
• DimCategory 
• DimShipper 
• DimCustomer 
• DimEmployee 
• DimProduct 

After loading the dimension tables, the FactSales table was loaded.
This loading order was important because the fact table depends on the dimension tables for
surrogate key lookups.

6.3 Transformations and Data Processing
During the ETL process, several transformations were applied to convert the raw data into a structured format suitable for the data warehouse.
·       Sorting - used before performing merge operations to ensure that data was properly aligned based on keys.
·       A Merge Join transformation - used to combine data from the Orders and Order Details tables. This allowed the system to create a complete view of each transaction.
·       Lookup transformations - used to retrieve surrogate keys from the dimension tables. These lookups were performed for Date, Customer, Product, Employee, Shipper, and Category dimensions. This ensured that the fact table stored references using surrogate keys instead of original source keys.
·       Derived Column transformations - used to create calculated fields. The SalesAmount was calculated using the formula:             SalesAmount = Quantity × UnitPrice × (1 − Discount)
 
In addition, the transaction create time was generated using the system date during the loading process.
Error handling was also considered during lookups by configuring the system to ignore rows with no matching entries. This helped to prevent ETL failures and ensured smooth data loading.
 
6.4 Fact Table Loading
The FactSales table was loaded after all dimension tables were successfully populated. This is because the fact table depends on the surrogate keys generated in the dimension tables.
The data for the fact table was created by combining the Orders and Order Details data using a merge join operation. After that, lookup transformations were applied to obtain the required surrogate keys from each dimension table.

Finally, the transformed data, including all foreign keys and calculated measures, was loaded into the FactSales table. This ensured that each record in the fact table was properly connected to all relevant dimensions.

7.    Accumulating Fact Implementation
In this project, an accumulating fact table approach was implemented to track the lifecycle of transactions. This was done by extending the FactSales table with additional columns to store transaction start time, completion time, and processing duration.
The following columns were added to the FactSales table:
• accm_txn_create_time - stores the time when the transaction record was created. 
• accm_txn_complete_time - stores the time when the transaction was completed. 
• txn_process_time_hours - stores the total processing time in hours between the create time and completion time. 
The accm_txn_create_time was set during the initial ETL process using the system date. This represents the time when the transaction was loaded into the data warehouse.

7.1   Completion Time Update Process
 
To update the transaction completion time, a separate dataset was prepared containing order IDs and completion timestamps. This dataset was stored as a CSV file named fact_completion_updates.csv.
 
A separate SSIS package named Update_Accumulating_Fact.dtsx was developed to handle the update process. The CSV file was first loaded into a staging table named FactCompletionUpdate in the DWBI_Staging database.
 
After loading the update data into the staging table, an SQL update operation was performed to update the corresponding records in the FactSales table. This update was performed using an INNER JOIN between FactSales and FactCompletionUpdate based on OrderID.


7.2  Process Time Calculation
 
After updating the completion time, the transaction processing time was calculated using SQL. The DATEDIFF function was used to calculate the difference in hours between accm_txn_create_time and accm_txn_complete_time.
 
Only records with a valid completion time were considered for this calculation. This ensured that the process time was calculated correctly without affecting incomplete transactions.

7.3  Handling Missing Transaction IDs
During the update process, it was possible that some order IDs in the update dataset did not exist in the FactSales table. To handle this scenario, the update operation was performed using an INNER JOIN. This ensured that only matching records were updated, while non-matching records were ignored without causing errors.
 
This approach provided a safe and reliable method for handling missing transaction IDs in the update process.
 
7.4  Validation of Results
 
Validation queries were used to verify the correctness of the update process. These queries were used to check whether completion times were updated correctly, whether process times were calculated properly, and whether any unmatched transaction IDs existed in the update dataset.
The results confirmed that the accumulating fact update process was successfully implemented.

1.  1.    Validation and Results
 
After completing the ETL process and accumulating fact updates, several validation checks were performed to ensure the correctness and completeness of the data warehouse.
First, the total number of records in the FactSales table was verified to confirm that all transactions were successfully loaded. The results showed that the expected number of records was present in the fact table.
Next, checks were performed to ensure that there were no NULL values in the foreign key columns of the fact table. This confirmed that all lookup transformations were successful and that each fact record was properly linked to the corresponding dimension tables.
Additional validation was done to verify the calculated SalesAmount values. Sample records were checked to ensure that the calculation based on Quantity, UnitPrice, and Discount was correct.
For the accumulating fact implementation, validation queries were used to confirm that accm_txn_complete_time was updated correctly and that txn_process_time_hours was calculated properly. The results showed that the process time values were consistent and logically correct.
Finally, checks were performed to identify any missing transaction IDs in the update dataset. The results confirmed that unmatched records were handled safely without causing any errors in the system.
These validation steps ensured that the data warehouse was accurate, consistent, and ready for analytical use.        
